For a few months now, I've been really concerned about the way we think and do things.

Every time I do something "automatically" — and by that I mean without thinking first, as if it had always been the only way to do it — I stop.

Why? Why do I check my emails every time I touch my phone? Why do I choose this store or buy this product instead of another? Why do I check Instagram even though I know I will end up seeing content I don't really want to see?

And more importantly: How much time do these reflexes take? What is the real quality of the output?

Even if I don't have the full answer yet, I'm getting closer.

## The Failure of Social Networks
For me, it's now obvious that social networks have taken a completely different direction from what they were made for.

I mean, it's not by scrolling, liking, and sharing photos of your friends, family members, or strangers that you really connect with them or get to know them.

Every social network is designed to keep you on the platform as long as possible, and to do that, you need to consume information without thinking about it. And that's the worst part for me.

I'm not even talking about TikTok, YouTube Shorts, or Instagram Reels.

## The Impact on Our Health
I like to watch and listen to the [Diary of a CEO](https://www.youtube.com/TheDiaryOfACEO).

The host has a calm voice and does not interrupt his guests, which is really appreciated.

As with other YouTube channels and podcasts, we should not take everything said as the absolute truth — but one thing all the speakers agree on is simple: our brain is not designed to process this much information.

And to be honest, a little introspection is all it takes to feel it. We don't need a "specialist" to confirm that.

Next time you spend what you think is a short time on social networks, when you're done take thirty seconds and just try to remember what you watched. Try also to remember what was happening around you while you were watching. And more importantly, try to honestly assess the real time you just spent.

You'll see that what felt like a quick 2-minute scroll actually took 10, you remember only one or two posts or pictures, and you have no idea what happened around you.

Worth noting: Silicon Valley engineers who build and maintain these social networks reportedly use them as little as possible and strictly forbid their children from using them.

I mean, what do you call a product that a group of people build, never consume or give to their own relatives, profit from, get users addicted to, and that is proven to be harmful to brain health?

It pretty much looks like a drug to me.

## A Positive Angle
Even if the way I write my observations seems negative — it is not. It's the opposite, and this blog is the proof.

I think we always have a choice. The power to choose what we want to do with our precious time.

For me, it won't be scrolling like an addict to see the curated lives of people I don't even care about, or checking emails every hour even when I'm not expecting anything important.

From now on, I will take time — to write this blog, to read other people's blogs, to think.

And if I need to connect with my family, why not simply meet up or call them?

Quality over quantity.
